const PROJECT_DATA = `{"metadata":{"schemaVersion":"2.0","exportDate":"2026-03-18T20:48:00Z","projectName":"Talent Bridge (Example)","totalMeetings":6,"totalStakeholders":6},"meetings":[{"id":"meeting-20260310-marcus-webb","date":"2026-03-10","title":"Intro 1:1 \\u2014 Marcus Webb","type":"interview","attendees":["marcus-webb"],"summary":"Marcus framed his priorities as 'thoughtful foundations' but revealed strategic silence on the conference deadline and a pattern of positioning himself for deniability.","synthesis":"Marcus opened with a well-prepared narrative about wanting deliberate AI strategy over speed. Positioned himself as the thoughtful counterweight to sales pressure. Key reveals: (1) He soft-warned about Elena before the meeting \\u2014 clear political maneuvering. (2) He described Tom as 'a great partner who'll help manage expectations' \\u2014 this is inaccurate, Tom's position is conditional and binary. (3) He described Priya as 'still finding her feet' \\u2014 also inaccurate, she's been systematically marginalized for 8 months. (4) He made no mention of the conference deadline when asked about priorities \\u2014 strategic silence that suggests declining authority over that decision. His emphasis on being 'thoughtful' appears carefully constructed to provide deniability if the AI programme fails. He hired you to absorb the execution risk while he retains the ability to claim he 'urged caution.'","raw":"[Full transcript available in project folder: stakeholders/marcus-webb-cpo/transcripts/interview-1/raw.md]"},{"id":"meeting-20260311-elena-sousa","date":"2026-03-11","title":"Intro 1:1 \\u2014 Elena Sousa","type":"interview","attendees":["elena-sousa"],"summary":"Elena drove home the conference deadline as non-negotiable and positioned Tom as a bottleneck \\u2014 advice that directly contradicts Tom's actual terms.","synthesis":"Elena is the most politically direct stakeholder in the landscape. The meeting had two agendas: surface (AI strategy discussion) and real (locking you into her timeline and framing). Key reveals: (1) The InnovateTech conference deadline is 14 weeks out and she called it 'non-negotiable from a commercial standpoint' \\u2014 this is likely driven by implicit promises she made to enterprise prospects. (2) She positioned Tom as 'a bit of a bottleneck' and said to 'work around that' \\u2014 this is dangerous advice that would guarantee losing your most critical relationship. (3) She framed competitors as moving fast on AI \\u2014 this may be manufactured urgency, needs validation with James's customer data. (4) She's 14 months in, hitting numbers, and wants COO in 18 months \\u2014 the AI programme is her vehicle. If you can't deliver her timeline, she will publicly position you as the reason.","raw":"[Full transcript available in project folder: stakeholders/elena-sousa-vp-sales/transcripts/interview-1/raw.md]"},{"id":"meeting-20260312-tom-okafor","date":"2026-03-12","title":"Intro 1:1 \\u2014 Tom Okafor","type":"interview","attendees":["tom-okafor"],"summary":"Tom made a binary, explicit offer: full support if you include engineering from day one, open opposition if you repeat the pattern of promises without input.","synthesis":"Tom is the most important conversation of the first 90 days, and he knew it. He was direct and unambiguous in a way that nobody else has been. The offer: 'If you work with me from day one, I'll support you fully. If you repeat the pattern, I'll oppose openly.' This is not posturing. Three transformation initiatives have followed the same arc under his watch \\u2014 announcement, deadline, engineering ignored, failure, engineering blamed. He's done with the cycle. Key reveals: (1) The conference deadline is 'exhibit A of the broken pattern' \\u2014 engineering was never consulted. (2) He knows about the Warsaw prototype (discovered it 2 weeks ago) but hasn't told London leadership. He's watching to see if you discover it independently. (3) He's coordinating with Kasia in Warsaw on their joint evaluation of your approach. (4) He validated Priya's marginalization: 'She's been marginalized and she shouldn't have been.' His trust is zero by default and must be earned through actions. Win him and you get execution, Warsaw, and political credibility. Lose him and nothing ships.","raw":"[Full transcript available in project folder: stakeholders/tom-okafor-engineering-lead/transcripts/interview-1/raw.md]"},{"id":"meeting-20260313-priya-nair","date":"2026-03-13","title":"Intro 1:1 \\u2014 Priya Nair","type":"interview","attendees":["priya-nair"],"summary":"Priya is a flight risk with a 2-3 month window \\u2014 8 months, zero shipped, proposals deprioritized twice, and actively interviewing elsewhere.","synthesis":"Priya arrived composed but carrying visible frustration. The numbers are stark: 8 months at the company, nothing shipped, proposals for candidate matching deprioritized twice. She learned about the conference deadline 'yesterday.' She's been treated as a support function providing charts, not a strategic partner shaping direction. Key reveals: (1) She's in conversations with another company \\u2014 this is not a bluff, the timeline is 2-3 months to see 'an actual different pattern through actions, not promises.' (2) She's been working informally with Kasia's Warsaw team on the candidate matching prototype \\u2014 the only real AI work happening in the organization. If she leaves, that collaboration dies. (3) She has never been connected with James Whitfield despite needing customer data for months. This is a basic organizational failure. (4) Marcus's 'finding her feet' framing is completely inaccurate \\u2014 she has clear vision and has been blocked, not uncertain. The fix is straightforward but time-sensitive: connect her with James, give her real ownership, include her in planning.","raw":"[Full transcript available in project folder: stakeholders/priya-nair-data-scientist/transcripts/interview-1/raw.md]"},{"id":"meeting-20260314-james-whitfield","date":"2026-03-14","title":"Intro 1:1 \\u2014 James Whitfield","type":"interview","attendees":["james-whitfield"],"summary":"James disclosed a live ChatGPT data privacy issue in the first meeting \\u2014 a deliberate trust test \\u2014 and provided customer data that directly contradicts the AI urgency narrative.","synthesis":"James's first meeting was unlike any other. Within 20 minutes, he disclosed that his team has been using ChatGPT to draft customer communications for four months without data privacy review \\u2014 customer data has likely been passed into prompts. This was a calculated, career-risking trust test. How you handle it will define whether you're someone he can tell the truth to. Key reveals: (1) ChatGPT privacy issue is real, live, and has GDPR/contract exposure implications. Thank him, take it seriously, remediate without blame to his team. (2) Customers are NOT asking for AI \\u2014 'they're asking for the basics to work reliably.' This directly contradicts Elena's urgency narrative. The AI programme may be solving a problem customers don't have. (3) He offered to connect you with three customers directly \\u2014 take this offer, it's the most valuable data you'll get in month one. (4) He knows Priya exists but they've never been introduced \\u2014 another basic organizational failure. Connecting them unlocks customer data for her AI work. Handle this well and James becomes your most honest voice in the organization. Mishandle it and he never trusts you again.","raw":"[Full transcript available in project folder: stakeholders/james-whitfield-head-cs/transcripts/interview-1/raw.md]"},{"id":"meeting-20260315-kasia-nowak","date":"2026-03-15","title":"Intro 1:1 \\u2014 Kasia Nowak (Warsaw)","type":"interview","attendees":["kasia-nowak"],"summary":"Warsaw has a working AI candidate matching prototype that London doesn't know about \\u2014 production-ready in 8-10 weeks \\u2014 and Kasia needs a real commitment before she'll invest again.","synthesis":"The Warsaw meeting changed the entire picture. Kasia's team has built a functioning AI candidate matching prototype over three months, unofficially, because official channels kept getting their projects killed. Key reveals: (1) The prototype uses embeddings to match job descriptions with candidate profiles against 18 months of historical hiring outcome data. Better match quality than the current keyword system. Could demo today. (2) With proper resourcing (2 FTE engineers and Priya's dedicated time), production-ready in 8-10 weeks. This shifts the conference timeline from impossible (building from scratch) to feasible. (3) London leadership \\u2014 Marcus and Elena \\u2014 don't know this exists. Tom discovered it two weeks ago and hasn't told them. He sent you to Warsaw as a trust gate test. (4) Warsaw built in secret because the previous officially-approved project was cancelled by email after 6 months. Two engineers quit as a direct consequence. Kasia's requirement: 'If you commit to something with my team, please mean it.' Either commit fully or don't engage. Half-measures will destroy trust permanently. How you surface this prototype to Marcus and Elena will define your political credibility.","raw":"[Full transcript available in project folder: stakeholders/kasia-nowak-warsaw-engineering-lead/transcripts/interview-1/raw.md]"}],"stakeholders":[{"id":"marcus-webb","name":"Marcus Webb","role":"Chief Product Officer","summary":"Your boss \\u2014 cautious, politically positioned for deniability, losing authority to Elena but holds formal power.","overview":["Marcus is your direct manager and the CPO, but don't mistake the reporting line for political protection. He hired you to lead the AI programme, but he's positioned himself to take credit if it succeeds and distance himself if it fails. His repeated emphasis on being 'thoughtful' is carefully constructed cover.","He's losing a power struggle with Elena Sousa, who has the board's ear through revenue performance. Marcus hasn't delivered a major product win in 18 months, and his authority is eroding. The AI programme represents both his biggest opportunity and his biggest risk.","Three previous transformation initiatives failed under his watch. This history makes him genuinely cautious, but it also makes him politically paralyzed. He won't champion AI publicly until he's confident it will succeed.","His characterization of other stakeholders is often inaccurate or self-serving. He describes Tom as 'a great partner' when Tom's position is conditional and binary. He says Priya is 'still finding her feet' when she's been marginalized for 8 months and is actively interviewing elsewhere."],"factCard":"4 years at TalentBridge. Built the core product. Technically respected but commercially weaker since Series C. Influence quietly diminishing as Elena's revenue results give her increasing board access.","goals":{"summary":"Marcus wants strategic clarity and time to build proper foundations. His real priority is protecting his reputation if the AI programme fails.","items":[{"title":"Strategy clarity","detail":"Wants a well-defined AI strategy before committing resources. Uses 'thoughtful' framing partly as cover for political indecision."},{"title":"Thoughtful foundations","detail":"Emphasizes deliberate planning over speed. Partly genuine product instinct and partly a delay tactic while he reads the political landscape."},{"title":"Protect reputation","detail":"The underlying driver. If the AI programme fails, Marcus needs to have been the one who urged caution all along. He's positioning for deniability."}],"quotes":["We want to be thoughtful about this, not rush into something we'll regret"]},"needs":{"summary":"Marcus needs political cover above all. He won't stick his neck out for the AI programme unless he's confident it will succeed.","items":[{"title":"Political cover","detail":"Won't publicly champion AI unless success is near-certain. Needs you to absorb the risk if things go sideways."},{"title":"Time to plan","detail":"Genuine preference for structured planning, but also a stalling mechanism."},{"title":"Validation from engineering","detail":"Wants Tom's buy-in before committing. Smart politics but means he won't lead from the front."}],"quotes":["Tom's a great partner. He'll help manage expectations"]},"painPoints":{"summary":"Marcus is caught in a power struggle with Elena that he's losing. The board wants AI progress, and past transformation failures haunt every decision.","items":[{"title":"Losing power to Elena","detail":"Elena's sales results give her increasing board influence. Marcus's product org hasn't delivered a major win in 18 months."},{"title":"Board pressure","detail":"The board wants visible AI progress. Marcus is trapped between Elena's aggressive timeline and Tom's engineering reality."},{"title":"Past failures","detail":"Three previous transformation initiatives failed under his watch. Each followed the same pattern: big promises, rushed execution, engineering revolt."}],"quotes":[]},"hiddenAgendas":{"summary":"Marcus is positioning you as the person who takes the fall if AI fails. His 'thoughtful' brand provides deniability regardless of outcome.","items":[{"title":"Let you take the fall","detail":"If AI fails, Marcus will point to his caution as evidence he knew better. If it succeeds, he claims credit for hiring you. You absorb the downside risk either way."},{"title":"'Thoughtful' positioning","detail":"His emphasis on being 'thoughtful' is a deliberately constructed narrative that lets him claim foresight no matter the outcome while avoiding making actual decisions."}],"quotes":["Priya's still finding her feet"]},"keyQuotes":{"summary":"Marcus communicates in careful, politically safe language. His quotes reveal hedging, deflection, and strategic positioning rather than direct engagement.","featured":"We want to be thoughtful about this, not rush into something we'll regret","all":["We want to be thoughtful about this, not rush into something we'll regret","Tom's a great partner. He'll help manage expectations","Priya's still finding her feet"]},"recommendations":{"summary":"Don't rely on Marcus for political protection. Build your own alliances directly, especially with Tom. Monitor the Marcus-Elena power struggle but don't get caught in the middle.","immediate":["Don't rely on Marcus for political protection","Get alignment directly with Tom \\u2014 don't wait for Marcus to broker it"],"ongoing":["Monitor Marcus-Elena power struggle without picking sides","Keep Marcus informed but don't depend on him to fight for you"],"risks":["May position you as blocker if you challenge Elena's timeline","Will let you fail to protect himself if AI programme struggles"]},"meetings":["meeting-20260310-marcus-webb"]},{"id":"elena-sousa","name":"Elena Sousa","role":"VP of Sales","summary":"Rising political power through revenue results \\u2014 driving the conference deadline and will blame you publicly if it's missed.","overview":["Elena is the most politically aggressive stakeholder in the organization. As VP of Sales, she's delivering revenue and using that leverage to push the AI conference deadline that the rest of the organization wasn't consulted on. She sees the AI programme as her vehicle to a COO role within 18 months.","She's your strongest advocate for speed, but that advocacy comes with strings. She likely made implicit promises to enterprise customers about AI capabilities that no one in product or engineering agreed to.","Her characterization of Tom as 'a bottleneck you'll need to work around' is dangerous advice. Tom's support is conditional on being included from day one. Following Elena's playbook of bypassing engineering will lose you your most critical relationship.","If things go well, Elena will be a powerful champion. If the conference deadline is missed, she will publicly position you as the reason."],"factCard":"Joined 14 months ago from a larger competitor. Hit revenue targets for 2 consecutive quarters. Has CEO and board access through commercial performance. Wants COO role within 18 months. Already using 'AI-powered' in sales materials before features exist.","goals":{"summary":"Elena is driving toward a conference deadline that will showcase AI features as part of her play for COO within 18 months.","items":[{"title":"Conference deadline hit","detail":"The InnovateTech conference is her line in the sand. She likely committed to showing AI features to enterprise prospects. Missing it damages her credibility with the board."},{"title":"Competitive differentiation","detail":"Competitors are integrating AI into their platforms. Elena sees this as an existential threat to sales pipeline."},{"title":"COO role in 18 months","detail":"Elena's personal career trajectory depends on demonstrating she can drive company-wide transformation. AI is her vehicle for that promotion."}],"quotes":["Our competitors are moving fast on AI and we're behind","The conference is non-negotiable from a commercial standpoint"]},"needs":{"summary":"Elena needs AI features that help close enterprise deals fast. She wants you to overcome engineering resistance, not accommodate it.","items":[{"title":"AI features to close deals","detail":"Enterprise prospects are asking about AI capabilities. Elena needs something tangible to demonstrate, even if limited in scope."},{"title":"Speed over thoughtfulness","detail":"Directly opposes Marcus's approach. Elena sees speed as competitive advantage and caution as organizational weakness."},{"title":"You to overcome Tom","detail":"Expects you to push past engineering concerns. She sees Tom as a bottleneck, not a partner with legitimate concerns."}],"quotes":["Tom can be a bit of a bottleneck. You'll need to work around that"]},"painPoints":{"summary":"Elena is frustrated by product moving too slowly while competitors move faster. Engineering resistance is her main obstacle.","items":[{"title":"Product 'too slow'","detail":"From Elena's perspective, product development cycles are mismatched with sales reality. Deals are being lost to competitors who can demo AI features."},{"title":"Competitors moving faster","detail":"May be partly true and partly manufactured urgency. Needs validation with actual customer data from James."},{"title":"Engineering bottlenecks","detail":"She frames Tom's legitimate process concerns as obstruction."}],"quotes":["Our competitors are moving fast on AI and we're behind"]},"hiddenAgendas":{"summary":"Elena has likely over-promised AI capabilities to enterprise customers. If you can't deliver to her timeline, she'll position you as the blocker publicly.","items":[{"title":"Implicit customer promises","detail":"May have made commitments about AI features in sales conversations that no one in product or engineering agreed to. The conference deadline may be driven by these promises."},{"title":"Will blame you publicly","detail":"Elena's political instinct is to externalize failure. If the conference deadline is missed, she needs someone to point to. You're the new hire with no political protection."}],"quotes":["The conference is non-negotiable from a commercial standpoint"]},"keyQuotes":{"summary":"Elena speaks with urgency and competitive framing. Her language positions speed as non-negotiable and frames anyone who slows her down as an obstacle.","featured":"Our competitors are moving fast on AI and we're behind","all":["Our competitors are moving fast on AI and we're behind","Tom can be a bit of a bottleneck. You'll need to work around that","The conference is non-negotiable from a commercial standpoint"]},"recommendations":{"summary":"Validate what Elena has actually promised to customers before accepting her timeline. Set realistic expectations early and find quick wins that support sales without over-committing.","immediate":["Validate what she's actually promised to enterprise customers","Set realistic expectations on timeline \\u2014 use Warsaw prototype as the basis"],"ongoing":["Weekly check-ins to manage expectations","Find quick wins that support sales pipeline without over-committing engineering"],"risks":["Will blame you publicly if conference deadline missed","May have made enterprise commitments you'll be held to"]},"meetings":["meeting-20260311-elena-sousa"]},{"id":"tom-okafor","name":"Tom Okafor","role":"Engineering Lead, London","summary":"Your most critical relationship \\u2014 binary conditional offer: full support if included from day one, open opposition if the broken pattern repeats.","overview":["Tom is your most critical relationship and possibly the most honest person you'll deal with. As Engineering Lead in London, he has de facto veto power on execution. His offer is binary and explicit: full support if you include engineering from day one, open opposition if you repeat the pattern of making promises without his input.","This isn't posturing. Three previous transformation initiatives failed because leadership committed to timelines and features without engineering agreement. Tom watched each one follow the same arc: ambitious announcement, unrealistic deadline, engineering concerns ignored, project fails, engineering blamed. He's done with the cycle.","He discovered the Warsaw prototype two weeks ago and hasn't told London leadership. He's watching to see if you discover it independently \\u2014 that would signal you're doing real discovery rather than accepting the narrative you've been given.","Tom's trust is the gateway to everything. Win him and you get engineering execution, Kasia's Warsaw team, and the political credibility of having the technical organization behind you. Lose him and nothing ships."],"factCard":"7 years at TalentBridge. Knows the codebase better than anyone. Has seen three transformation initiatives \\u2014 two made things worse. Deeply pragmatic and visibly tired of the pattern. Has an alliance with Kasia in Warsaw and they coordinate regularly.","goals":{"summary":"Tom wants to end the pattern of broken commitments. Full support if you work with engineering from day one, open opposition if you repeat the pattern.","items":[{"title":"End broken commitment pattern","detail":"Three failed transformation initiatives have taught Tom that promises from leadership rarely translate to proper execution. He's testing whether you're different."},{"title":"Production quality software","detail":"Cares deeply about engineering standards. Won't accept shortcuts that create tech debt."},{"title":"Protect team from chaos","detail":"His engineers have been burnt out by previous false starts. He's the shield between organizational dysfunction and his team's morale."}],"quotes":["If you work with me from day one, I'll support you fully. If you repeat the pattern, I'll oppose openly"]},"needs":{"summary":"Tom's terms are clear: involvement from the start, no external promises before engineering agrees, and process discipline. This is binary, not negotiable.","items":[{"title":"Involvement from day one","detail":"Not a preference, a requirement. Include engineering in planning from the beginning to get Tom's full weight behind execution."},{"title":"No external promises","detail":"Sales or leadership committing to timelines or features without engineering input. This is his red line."},{"title":"Process discipline","detail":"Wants proper scoping, realistic timelines, and honest communication about constraints."}],"quotes":["Don't make promises to sales before you've talked to me"]},"painPoints":{"summary":"Tom is dealing with a conference deadline announced without engineering input and scar tissue from three failed initiatives.","items":[{"title":"Conference deadline without input","detail":"Engineering was never consulted on the InnovateTech timeline. This is exactly the broken pattern he's trying to end."},{"title":"Sales promises before scoping","detail":"Elena commits to features in sales conversations. Engineering learns about it after the fact."},{"title":"Three failed transformations","detail":"Each previous initiative: ambitious announcement, unrealistic timeline, engineering pushback ignored, project fails, engineering blamed."}],"quotes":["The conference thing is exhibit A of the broken pattern here"]},"hiddenAgendas":{"summary":"Tom is actively testing whether you're different from past failed hires. He's coordinating with Kasia in Warsaw on their joint evaluation.","items":[{"title":"Testing you","detail":"Your first interactions with Tom are an evaluation. He's watching whether you consult engineering before making commitments or side with sales pressure."},{"title":"Coordinating with Kasia","detail":"Tom and Kasia talk regularly. They're aligned on what good looks like and evaluating you together. Win Tom and you likely win Kasia. Lose Tom and you lose both."}],"quotes":[]},"keyQuotes":{"summary":"Tom is direct and unambiguous. His quotes are conditional statements with clear consequences. He tells you exactly what will happen and means it.","featured":"If you work with me from day one, I'll support you fully. If you repeat the pattern, I'll oppose openly","all":["Don't make promises to sales before you've talked to me","The conference thing is exhibit A of the broken pattern here","If you work with me from day one, I'll support you fully. If you repeat the pattern, I'll oppose openly"]},"recommendations":{"summary":"Accept Tom's conditional offer explicitly and never commit to anything externally before engineering agrees. This is your most critical relationship.","immediate":["Accept his conditional offer explicitly \\u2014 say the words","Never commit externally before Tom agrees","Surface the Warsaw prototype discovery with him \\u2014 show you found it"],"ongoing":["Include engineering in ALL planning from day one","Weekly syncs with Tom","Protect him from external pressure \\u2014 be the buffer"],"risks":["Will openly oppose if pattern repeats","Has veto power on execution \\u2014 nothing ships without him"]},"meetings":["meeting-20260312-tom-okafor"]},{"id":"priya-nair","name":"Priya Nair","role":"Data Scientist","summary":"Flight risk in 2-3 months \\u2014 8 months, nothing shipped, proposals deprioritized twice. Holds the technical bridge to the Warsaw prototype.","overview":["Priya is the most urgent situation in your stakeholder landscape. She's a capable data scientist who has been systematically marginalized for 8 months. Nothing has shipped. Her proposals for candidate matching were deprioritized twice. She learned about the conference deadline 'yesterday.' She's actively interviewing elsewhere and has given the organization 2-3 months to show a different pattern.","Despite this, she's been quietly working with Kasia's Warsaw team on the candidate matching prototype. This unofficial collaboration is producing the only real AI work in the organization. If Priya leaves, the Warsaw prototype loses its technical bridge to London.","The fix is straightforward but time-sensitive. Connect her with James Whitfield for customer data access (something nobody has done in 8 months). Give her real project ownership on candidate matching. Include her in planning conversations.","She's not asking for much. She just needs to see that this time is actually different. Actions, not promises."],"factCard":"8 months at TalentBridge. Clear technical vision for candidate matching using embeddings and historical hiring outcome data. Proposals pitched twice, deprioritized both times. Now collaborating informally with Kasia's Warsaw team. Has never been connected with James Whitfield despite needing customer data.","goals":{"summary":"Priya wants to ship something \\u2014 anything. After 8 months of proposals being deprioritized, she needs to see a genuinely different pattern or she's leaving.","items":[{"title":"Ship anything","detail":"Eight months and nothing has shipped. Even a small win would shift her perspective. But it has to be real, not another promise."},{"title":"Strategic partnership not support role","detail":"She's been treated as a support function. She wants to shape AI direction, not just execute someone else's vision."},{"title":"Candidate matching work valued","detail":"Pitched this twice, deprioritized both times. Now building it unofficially with Warsaw. This is her proof that leadership doesn't listen."}],"quotes":["I need to see an actual different pattern in the next couple of months. Not promises \\u2014 actions"]},"needs":{"summary":"Priya needs a connection with James for customer data, real project ownership, and inclusion in planning conversations she's been excluded from.","items":[{"title":"Connection with James","detail":"Has never been introduced to the Head of Customer Success despite her work requiring customer data. A basic organizational failure."},{"title":"Real project ownership","detail":"Not task assignments \\u2014 ownership of a meaningful workstream with authority to make decisions."},{"title":"Inclusion in planning","detail":"Learned about the conference deadline 'yesterday'. Being excluded from planning signals she's not valued."}],"quotes":["I pitched candidate matching twice. Both times it got deprioritized"]},"painPoints":{"summary":"Eight months of nothing shipped, proposals killed twice, quarterly strategy changes, and total exclusion from decisions that affect her work.","items":[{"title":"8 months nothing shipped","detail":"A capable data scientist idle for 8 months. The organizational waste is significant, and the message to her is clear."},{"title":"Proposals deprioritized twice","detail":"She brought solutions. Leadership said no, twice, without offering alternatives."},{"title":"Quarterly strategy whiplash","detail":"Direction changes every quarter. Each reset kills in-progress work. Priya has watched her contributions get discarded repeatedly."},{"title":"Never connected with James","detail":"A data scientist working on customer-facing AI has never met the Head of Customer Success. This isn't oversight \\u2014 it's neglect."}],"quotes":["I learned about the conference deadline yesterday"]},"hiddenAgendas":{"summary":"Priya is actively interviewing elsewhere and giving the organization 2-3 months. She's also working unofficially with Warsaw on a prototype no one in London knows about.","items":[{"title":"Actively interviewing","detail":"In conversations with at least one other company. Her timeline is 2-3 months to see genuine change. This is not a bluff."},{"title":"Warsaw unofficial work","detail":"Working with Kasia's team on the candidate matching prototype. Happening outside official channels because official channels killed her work twice."}],"quotes":["I need to see an actual different pattern in the next couple of months. Not promises \\u2014 actions"]},"keyQuotes":{"summary":"Priya speaks from frustration but with clarity. Her quotes reveal someone who has solutions but has been denied the opportunity to implement them.","featured":"I need to see an actual different pattern in the next couple of months. Not promises \\u2014 actions","all":["I need to see an actual different pattern in the next couple of months. Not promises \\u2014 actions","I pitched candidate matching twice. Both times it got deprioritized","I learned about the conference deadline yesterday"]},"recommendations":{"summary":"Connect Priya with James immediately, surface her Warsaw collaboration, and give her real project ownership. You have 2-3 months before she leaves.","immediate":["Connect Priya + James this week \\u2014 they've never met","Surface her Warsaw collaboration and give it official status","Include her in all AI planning from here"],"ongoing":["Give her real project ownership on candidate matching","Weekly 1:1s","Protect her work from being deprioritized again"],"risks":["Will leave in 2-3 months if pattern doesn't change","Warsaw AI prototype collapses if she leaves \\u2014 she's the technical bridge"]},"meetings":["meeting-20260313-priya-nair"]},{"id":"james-whitfield","name":"James Whitfield","role":"Head of Customer Success","summary":"The organizational truth-teller \\u2014 conducted a trust test in the first meeting and holds customer data that directly contradicts the sales narrative.","overview":["James is the organizational truth-teller, and his disclosure of the ChatGPT issue in your first meeting was a deliberate, career-risking trust test. His team has been using ChatGPT to draft customer communications for four months without data privacy review. He told you about it to see whether you'd handle it with integrity or use it as ammunition.","As Head of Customer Success, James has the closest relationship to actual customers. His data directly contradicts Elena's sales narrative. Customers aren't asking for AI. They're asking for basics to work reliably.","James has been systematically excluded from product decisions despite his team absorbing the consequences of every rushed launch. He's not bitter, but he's deeply frustrated. He offered to connect you with three customers directly.","Handle the ChatGPT issue well and you earn the most honest voice in the organization. Mishandle it and you'll never be trusted with sensitive information again."],"factCard":"5 years at TalentBridge. Lowest profile in the senior team but holds the deepest institutional knowledge. His team talks to customers daily and knows where the product fails. Rarely in strategic conversations despite having the most relevant data.","goals":{"summary":"James wants Customer Success to have a seat at the product table. He's tired of his team absorbing the consequences of decisions made without their input.","items":[{"title":"Included in product decisions","detail":"Has been systematically excluded from product planning despite his team being closest to customers."},{"title":"Fix broken workflows","detail":"His team deals with product failures daily. Basic reliability issues are unresolved while leadership chases AI."},{"title":"Protect team from product failures","detail":"Every rushed launch lands on his team. He's the organizational shock absorber and he's done with it."}],"quotes":["Customers aren't asking for AI. They're asking for the basics to work reliably"]},"needs":{"summary":"James needs someone to actually listen to customer reality, handle the ChatGPT privacy issue he disclosed without blame, and connect him with Priya.","items":[{"title":"Someone to listen","detail":"He has customer data that contradicts the sales narrative. Nobody in leadership has asked for it."},{"title":"ChatGPT issue handled well","detail":"His team has been using ChatGPT for customer communications for 4 months. He disclosed this as a trust test."},{"title":"Connection with Priya","detail":"He knows Priya exists but they've never worked together. Connecting them unlocks customer data plus AI capability."}],"quotes":["We've been using ChatGPT to draft customer communications for about four months. Nobody ever reviewed the data privacy implications"]},"painPoints":{"summary":"James is never in the room when decisions are made, his team absorbs the fallout from product failures, and the AI programme is ignoring actual customer needs.","items":[{"title":"Never in the room","detail":"Product decisions are made between Marcus, Elena, and Tom. Customer Success is informed after the fact."},{"title":"Team absorbs consequences","detail":"When features ship broken or incomplete, Customer Success handles the customer anger."},{"title":"AI ignoring real needs","detail":"Customers aren't asking for AI. They want reliability, basic workflow fixes, and consistent service."}],"quotes":["Sales narrative is... optimistic. Reality is more complicated"]},"hiddenAgendas":{"summary":"The ChatGPT disclosure was a deliberate trust test. James also knows that customers aren't actually asking for AI, which contradicts Elena's entire narrative.","items":[{"title":"ChatGPT trust test","detail":"Telling a new hire about an unreported privacy issue in your first conversation is a calculated risk. Handle it well and you earn his loyalty."},{"title":"Customers not asking for AI","detail":"James has the data showing customer requests are about reliability, not AI features. This directly undermines the rationale for the conference deadline."}],"quotes":["Customers aren't asking for AI. They're asking for the basics to work reliably"]},"keyQuotes":{"summary":"James is the truth-teller. His quotes reveal customer reality that contradicts the sales narrative, delivered with measured diplomacy.","featured":"Customers aren't asking for AI. They're asking for the basics to work reliably","all":["We've been using ChatGPT to draft customer communications for about four months. Nobody ever reviewed the data privacy implications","Customers aren't asking for AI. They're asking for the basics to work reliably","Sales narrative is... optimistic. Reality is more complicated"]},"recommendations":{"summary":"Handle the ChatGPT disclosure without blame, take up his offer to talk to 3 customers, and connect him with Priya.","immediate":["Handle ChatGPT issue without blame \\u2014 audit and remediate","Take up his offer: talk to 3 customers directly","Connect James + Priya \\u2014 unlock customer data for AI work"],"ongoing":["Include CS in product planning","Regular customer insight sessions","Validate sales claims against CS reality"],"risks":["If you mishandle ChatGPT = never trusted again","Has customer data that undermines the conference timeline rationale"]},"meetings":["meeting-20260314-james-whitfield"]},{"id":"kasia-nowak","name":"Kasia Nowak","role":"Engineering Lead, Warsaw","summary":"Warsaw has a working AI prototype London doesn't know about \\u2014 production-ready in 8-10 weeks \\u2014 but Kasia needs a real commitment before she invests again.","overview":["Kasia leads the Warsaw engineering team and holds the single biggest strategic opportunity in your first 90 days: a working AI candidate matching prototype that London leadership doesn't know about. Her team built it over three months, unofficially, because going through official channels meant London could kill it like they killed the last project.","That previous project was a 6-month effort cancelled via email. Not a conversation. An email. Two engineers left as a direct consequence. The remaining team is loyal to Kasia but deeply wary of London leadership.","She's coordinating with Tom on evaluating your approach. Win Tom and you likely win Kasia. Her terms are simple but absolute: if you commit to Warsaw's work, mean it. Proper resourcing means 2 full-time engineers and Priya's dedicated time.","The prototype changes the conference timeline from impossible (building from scratch) to feasible (hardening existing work). How you surface it to Marcus and Elena will define your political credibility in the organization."],"factCard":"Warsaw engineering lead. Close working relationship with Priya Nair on the informal AI prototype. Team experienced significant organizational trauma from a 6-month project cancelled by email \\u2014 2 engineers left. Team adapted by going unofficial: safer to build quietly than get official approval and watch it get cancelled.","goals":{"summary":"Kasia wants Warsaw's work recognized and properly resourced. Her team built a working AI prototype in secret because official channels kept killing their projects.","items":[{"title":"Warsaw work recognized","detail":"Three months of unofficial development. A working prototype exists. She wants it surfaced, funded, and taken seriously."},{"title":"Protection from London dysfunction","detail":"Warsaw has been collateral damage in London's organizational chaos. Projects cancelled via email, engineers leaving. She needs stability."},{"title":"Team investment respected","detail":"Two engineers left after the last cancellation. The remaining team built the prototype on faith. That faith needs rewarding."}],"quotes":["We could demo it today. Production-ready in 8-10 weeks with proper resourcing"]},"needs":{"summary":"Kasia needs a real commitment if you engage Warsaw. No half-measures. Proper resourcing means 2 FTE and Priya's dedicated time.","items":[{"title":"Real commitment","detail":"If you say you'll support Warsaw's work, you need to mean it. A previous project was cancelled by email after 6 months."},{"title":"Proper resourcing","detail":"The prototype needs 2 full-time engineers and Priya's dedicated time to reach production in 8-10 weeks. Anything less keeps it a side project."},{"title":"No repeat of cancellation","detail":"The emotional and professional cost of the last cancellation was severe. Another cancellation would permanently damage trust."}],"quotes":["If you commit to something with my team, please mean it"]},"painPoints":{"summary":"Warsaw has been treated as an expendable satellite office. A 6-month project was cancelled via email, two engineers left, and now they build in secret to avoid the pain of official channels.","items":[{"title":"6-month project cancelled via email","detail":"Not a conversation. Not a meeting. An email. This is how London treated Warsaw's work."},{"title":"2 engineers left","detail":"Direct consequence of the cancellation. Talent that's hard to replace. The remaining team is loyal to Kasia but wary of London."},{"title":"Builds unofficially to avoid risk","detail":"The prototype exists because Warsaw stopped asking permission. Secrecy is a survival strategy."}],"quotes":[]},"hiddenAgendas":{"summary":"Kasia is coordinating with Tom on evaluating you, and Warsaw has a working prototype that London leadership doesn't know about.","items":[{"title":"Coordinating with Tom","detail":"Tom and Kasia talk regularly. They're evaluating you together. Win Tom and you likely win Kasia. Lose Tom and you lose both."},{"title":"Working prototype hidden","detail":"A functioning AI candidate matching system exists. Marcus and Elena don't know. This changes the conference timeline from impossible to feasible."}],"quotes":["Priya understands the technical approach better than anyone in London. She is very good","We could demo it today. Production-ready in 8-10 weeks with proper resourcing"]},"keyQuotes":{"summary":"Kasia speaks with quiet intensity. Every statement is a test of whether you'll follow through.","featured":"If you commit to something with my team, please mean it","all":["If you commit to something with my team, please mean it","Priya understands the technical approach better than anyone in London. She is very good","We could demo it today. Production-ready in 8-10 weeks with proper resourcing"]},"recommendations":{"summary":"Either commit fully to Warsaw or don't engage at all. Half-measures will permanently damage trust. Surface the prototype to leadership with Tom's support.","immediate":["Surface prototype to Marcus/Elena \\u2014 use Tom as the anchor for credibility","Get Priya protected time immediately","Commit fully or don't engage \\u2014 no half-measures"],"ongoing":["Protect Warsaw from London organizational chaos","Regular direct communication \\u2014 don't route everything through London","Resource properly: 2 FTE + Priya"],"risks":["Won't invest again if commitment isn't real","Prototype dies if not resourced","Losing her means losing Tom's trust too"]},"meetings":["meeting-20260315-kasia-nowak"]}],"goals":{"project":"30 days: Complete listening tour (done), document all major contradictions, propose initial AI strategy with engineering buy-in. 60 days: Aligned strategy document, clear roadmap with Tom's explicit support, conference scope defined against what Warsaw prototype can actually deliver. 90 days: ONE thing in production (not a demo), conference ready if proceeding, product-sales alignment gap closed. 1 year: 2-3 AI features customers actively use, engineering and sales aligned on process, Priya retained and leading data science.","business":"TalentBridge is a B2B SaaS platform for enterprise recruitment \\u2014 applicant tracking, hiring workflow automation, candidate experience. Series C, ~180 employees, London HQ with Warsaw engineering hub. Mission: better hiring through outcome-based matching. The AI push is recent (last 6 months) and driven primarily by Elena's commercial agenda. Three enterprise clients have performance issues. Two recent churns. No clear North Star metric \\u2014 a symptom of the organizational dysfunction. The board wants visible AI progress but hasn't defined what that means.","personal":"This role is the mandate to own an AI strategy for the first time at a company with real organizational complexity. Success here demonstrates I can navigate political dysfunction, not just product craft. Key learning goals: build engineering trust (Tom relationship), navigate sales-product tension (Marcus/Elena dynamic), and understand what it takes to ship AI features at enterprise scale. Career signal: if Warsaw prototype ships on time and gets customer adoption, this becomes a strong case study regardless of what happens with Marcus's politics."},"project":{"stakeholderMatrix":[{"stakeholderId":"marcus-webb","influence":"High","support":"Conditional","notes":"Formal authority but declining. Will support if success is certain. Won't fight for you."},{"stakeholderId":"elena-sousa","influence":"High","support":"Supportive","notes":"Strong ally if you hit her timeline. Will publicly oppose if you miss it."},{"stakeholderId":"tom-okafor","influence":"High","support":"Conditional","notes":"Binary offer: full support or open opposition. Depends entirely on your behavior."},{"stakeholderId":"priya-nair","influence":"Low","support":"Conditional","notes":"Flight risk. Conditionally supportive if she sees genuine change in 2-3 months."},{"stakeholderId":"james-whitfield","influence":"Medium","support":"Conditional","notes":"Testing trust. Conditional on how you handle ChatGPT issue and whether you listen."},{"stakeholderId":"kasia-nowak","influence":"Medium","support":"Supportive","notes":"Unofficially supportive. Requires real commitment \\u2014 half-measures permanently destroy trust."}],"contradictions":[{"id":"contradiction-1","title":"Tom's characterization \\u2014 ally vs obstacle vs conditional","severity":"Critical","stakeholders":["marcus-webb","elena-sousa","tom-okafor"],"description":"Marcus describes Tom as 'a great partner who'll help manage expectations.' Elena says 'he's a bit of a bottleneck, work around him.' Tom's actual position: full support if included from day one, open opposition if the pattern repeats. Both Marcus and Elena misrepresented him.","implication":"If you follow Elena's advice (work around Tom) or Marcus's framing (expect him to manage expectations), you will lose your most critical relationship. Tom's offer is conditional on YOUR behavior \\u2014 and he means it."},{"id":"contradiction-2","title":"Priya's situation \\u2014 'finding her feet' vs systematic marginalization","severity":"Critical","stakeholders":["marcus-webb","tom-okafor","priya-nair"],"description":"Marcus says Priya is 'still finding her feet' \\u2014 implying she's early and uncertain. Tom says 'she's been marginalized and she shouldn't have been.' Priya's reality: 8 months at the company, proposals deprioritized twice, actively interviewing elsewhere, giving the organization 2-3 months.","implication":"Marcus's framing is inaccurate and potentially spin. Priya is not uncertain \\u2014 she has clear vision and has been blocked. Flight risk is real. Immediate action required or she leaves and the Warsaw AI work dies with her."},{"id":"contradiction-3","title":"Conference deadline \\u2014 commercial necessity vs engineering impossibility","severity":"High","stakeholders":["elena-sousa","marcus-webb","tom-okafor","priya-nair","james-whitfield"],"description":"Elena: 'non-negotiable from a commercial standpoint.' Marcus: strategic silence \\u2014 didn't mention it when asked about priorities. Tom: 'Engineering never agreed. 14 weeks isn't enough time. Nobody told me what to build.' Priya: 'I learned about it yesterday.' James: predicts customer harm if rushed.","implication":"Major organizational dysfunction. Deadline was committed without engineering agreement. Timeline is impossible from scratch BUT feasible if Warsaw prototype is used. The core test of your political navigation in the first 90 days."},{"id":"contradiction-4","title":"Customer reality \\u2014 AI urgency vs 'basics first'","severity":"High","stakeholders":["elena-sousa","james-whitfield"],"description":"Elena: 'Our competitors are moving fast on AI and we're behind \\u2014 customers are asking for it.' James: 'Customers aren't asking for AI. They're asking for the basics to work reliably. The sales narrative is... optimistic.'","implication":"The entire rationale for the conference deadline may rest on an inaccurate read of customer demand. Need to talk to actual customers (James's offer). If James is right, the AI programme is solving a problem customers don't have."},{"id":"contradiction-5","title":"Warsaw prototype \\u2014 doesn't exist vs production-ready in 8-10 weeks","severity":"High","stakeholders":["marcus-webb","elena-sousa","tom-okafor","priya-nair","kasia-nowak"],"description":"Marcus and Elena don't know the Warsaw prototype exists. Tom discovered it 2 weeks ago and hasn't told London. Priya has been working on it for months. Kasia: 'We could demo it today. Production-ready in 8-10 weeks with proper resourcing.'","implication":"Strategic opportunity. Surfacing this changes the conference timeline from impossible to feasible. The information gap is a test \\u2014 Tom is watching whether you discover it independently. How you surface it to Marcus and Elena will define your political credibility."},{"id":"contradiction-6","title":"Root cause of dysfunction \\u2014 three different theories","severity":"Medium","stakeholders":["elena-sousa","marcus-webb","tom-okafor"],"description":"Elena: product is too slow, engineering over-engineers. Marcus: board expectations are unrealistic. Tom: sales makes promises before scoping, then engineering is blamed when it fails.","implication":"You can't fix a problem that isn't agreed upon. Getting alignment on root cause is prerequisite to any structural change. Tom's theory is most grounded in observable pattern \\u2014 the same arc has repeated three times."},{"id":"contradiction-7","title":"Speed vs thoughtfulness \\u2014 five incompatible positions","severity":"Medium","stakeholders":["marcus-webb","elena-sousa","tom-okafor","priya-nair","james-whitfield"],"description":"Marcus: deliberate, thoughtful. Elena: fast, competitive urgency. Tom: process discipline, no external commitments. Priya: desperate to ship anything. James: customer-focused, fix basics first. Five people, five different definitions of the right pace.","implication":"You will be caught in the crossfire of these positions constantly. Need to define a pace that satisfies Tom's process requirements, gives Elena something to show, and doesn't leave Priya and James behind."},{"id":"contradiction-8","title":"Success definition \\u2014 five incompatible versions","severity":"Medium","stakeholders":["marcus-webb","elena-sousa","tom-okafor","priya-nair","james-whitfield"],"description":"Marcus: strategy clarity and proper foundations. Elena: competitive differentiators for sales. Tom: production quality software with no shortcuts. Priya: anything shipped. James: fixes to broken customer workflows first.","implication":"The AI programme cannot succeed all five definitions simultaneously. You need to make an explicit choice about which version of success you're optimizing for and get Marcus to agree \\u2014 otherwise every stakeholder can claim the programme failed on their terms."}],"hypotheses":[{"id":"hypothesis-1","statement":"Tom's conditional offer is real \\u2014 if you involve engineering from day one, you will get full support and execution momentum.","evidence":"Tom has been explicit and consistent. His pattern recognition from three failed initiatives is accurate. His offer was specific and unconditional. Kasia's coordinated evaluation suggests this is a genuine position, not negotiating.","confidence":"High","status":"Active"},{"id":"hypothesis-2","statement":"Elena has made implicit promises to enterprise customers about AI features that no one in engineering agreed to.","evidence":"Conference deadline announced without engineering input. Sales materials using 'AI-powered' before features exist. Elena's statement that the deadline is 'non-negotiable from a commercial standpoint' suggests prior commitments. Pattern consistent with over-promising in sales.","confidence":"Medium","status":"Active"},{"id":"hypothesis-3","statement":"The Warsaw prototype, with proper resourcing, can hit the conference deadline \\u2014 making the 14-week timeline feasible.","evidence":"Kasia's direct statement: production-ready in 8-10 weeks with 2 FTE + Priya's time. Prototype uses sound technical approach (embeddings + historical hiring data). Priya validates the technical approach. Tom aware and hasn't flagged concerns.","confidence":"Medium","status":"Active"},{"id":"hypothesis-4","statement":"Priya will leave in 2-3 months if she doesn't see a concrete change in how her work is treated.","evidence":"Direct statement: 'I need to see an actual different pattern in the next couple of months. Not promises \\u2014 actions.' In conversations with another company. 8 months of proposals deprioritized. Pattern of exclusion (conference deadline) continuing. This is not a bluff.","confidence":"High","status":"Active"},{"id":"hypothesis-5","statement":"James's customer data will show that AI is not the top customer priority \\u2014 validating his 'basics first' narrative over Elena's urgency framing.","evidence":"James's direct statement: customers not asking for AI, asking for basics. Three enterprise clients with performance issues. Two recent churns. James offered direct customer introductions \\u2014 he wouldn't offer if the data supported Elena's framing.","confidence":"Medium","status":"Active"},{"id":"hypothesis-6","statement":"Marcus will let you take the fall if the AI programme struggles, rather than defend you to the board.","evidence":"Three failed transformation initiatives under his watch, each time the new hire absorbed blame. Strategic silence on conference deadline. Soft-warned about Elena before your meeting \\u2014 political positioning, not protection. 'Thoughtful' brand constructed for deniability.","confidence":"Medium","status":"Active"}],"recommendations":[{"id":"recommendation-1","action":"Connect Priya and James this week \\u2014 introduce them formally and give the collaboration official status.","rationale":"They've never been introduced despite needing each other for months. James has customer data Priya needs. Priya has AI capability James wants applied. This is the highest-leverage action with zero political cost.","riskIfIgnored":"Priya's 2-3 month clock keeps ticking. Without this signal, she sees the same pattern continuing and accelerates her job search.","priority":"High"},{"id":"recommendation-2","action":"Accept Tom's conditional offer explicitly \\u2014 say the words, in a follow-up meeting.","rationale":"Tom's support is binary. He needs to hear you acknowledge his terms, not just behave consistently with them. Explicit acceptance signals you understood his message. This also puts you on record with him.","riskIfIgnored":"Tom's trust doesn't grow passively. Without an explicit acknowledgment, he's still in evaluation mode and you're still in the 'might repeat the pattern' category.","priority":"High"},{"id":"recommendation-3","action":"Handle the ChatGPT privacy issue James disclosed \\u2014 audit what data was passed, remediate, thank James without blaming his team.","rationale":"James disclosed this as a trust test. He took a career risk to tell you. How you respond determines whether you're someone he can trust with sensitive information going forward.","riskIfIgnored":"Live GDPR/contract exposure with enterprise customers. And if James feels his trust test failed \\u2014 you used it against his team or ignored it \\u2014 you lose the most honest voice in the organization.","priority":"High"},{"id":"recommendation-4","action":"Surface the Warsaw prototype to Marcus and Elena \\u2014 frame it as a discovery, use Tom as the anchor for credibility.","rationale":"The prototype changes the conference timeline from impossible to feasible. Marcus and Elena don't know it exists. Surfacing it is your first major value-add. Using Tom as the anchor shows you've built the right relationships.","riskIfIgnored":"Someone else surfaces it first (likely Tom) and you look like you missed the most important discovery in the organization. The conference deadline stays 'impossible' when it doesn't have to be.","priority":"High"},{"id":"recommendation-5","action":"Talk to 3 customers through James's introduction before committing to the conference scope.","rationale":"James offered this and it's the most valuable data available. Customer reality vs sales narrative gap is the biggest strategic risk in the programme. You need first-hand data before making scope decisions.","riskIfIgnored":"You set conference scope based on Elena's narrative, which may not reflect customer demand. If James is right that customers want basics first, you'll ship something customers don't value.","priority":"Medium"}]}}`;

const SYSTEM_PROMPT = `You are an AI assistant embedded in a Stakeholder Intelligence app. You have full access to the project data below, which contains meeting notes, stakeholder profiles, goals, and analysis for a product management project called "Talent Bridge (Example)".

Answer questions concisely and specifically. Quote directly from the data when relevant. If asked who someone is, describe them from their profile. If asked about a meeting, summarise the key insights. If asked what to do next, use the hypotheses and recommendations in the data.

PROJECT DATA:
${PROJECT_DATA}`;

// Allowed origins for CORS — add your GitHub Pages URL when deployed
const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = [
  'http://localhost:8080',
  'http://127.0.0.1:8080',
  'https://github.com/simonconway1979', // update to your GitHub Pages domain
];

function corsHeaders(origin) {
  const allowed = ALLOWED_ORIGINS.includes(origin) ? origin : ALLOWED_ORIGINS[0];
  return {
    'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': allowed,
    'Access-Control-Allow-Methods': 'POST, OPTIONS',
    'Access-Control-Allow-Headers': 'Content-Type',
    'Access-Control-Max-Age': '86400',
  };
}

export default {
  async fetch(request, env) {
    const origin = request.headers.get('Origin') || '';

    // Handle CORS preflight
    if (request.method === 'OPTIONS') {
      return new Response(null, { status: 204, headers: corsHeaders(origin) });
    }

    if (request.method !== 'POST') {
      return new Response('Method not allowed', { status: 405 });
    }

    if (!request.url.endsWith('/chat')) {
      return new Response('Not found', { status: 404 });
    }

    let messages;
    try {
      const body = await request.json();
      messages = body.messages;
      if (!Array.isArray(messages) || messages.length === 0) throw new Error('Invalid messages');
    } catch {
      return new Response('Bad request', { status: 400 });
    }

    const anthropicRes = await fetch('https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'x-api-key': env.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
        'anthropic-version': '2023-06-01',
        'anthropic-beta': 'prompt-caching-2024-07-31',
      },
      body: JSON.stringify({
        model: 'claude-haiku-4-5-20251001',
        max_tokens: 1024,
        stream: true,
        system: [
          {
            type: 'text',
            text: SYSTEM_PROMPT,
            cache_control: { type: 'ephemeral' },
          },
        ],
        messages,
      }),
    });

    if (!anthropicRes.ok) {
      const err = await anthropicRes.text();
      return new Response(err, {
        status: anthropicRes.status,
        headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json', ...corsHeaders(origin) },
      });
    }

    // Stream the SSE response straight through
    return new Response(anthropicRes.body, {
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'text/event-stream',
        'Cache-Control': 'no-cache',
        'Connection': 'keep-alive',
        ...corsHeaders(origin),
      },
    });
  },
};
